   =20
 =20

Let=E2=80=99s say you want to make an animated web series about cats. Not j=
ust any cats, though: The exciting twist in this series is that these cats =
smoke marijuana.
  [1]
=C2=A0You care a lot about this idea, and you want the production to be per=
fect. You want to hire an amazing cast; you want celebrities like,  I swear=
 I am not making this up, Ashton Kutcher, Mila Kunis, Seth MacFarlane, Jane=
 Fonda,=C2=A0Chris Rock and, of course, Vitalik Buterin (as Lord Catsington=
). That takes money.
To raise the money, you go out to investors on the internet and say =E2=80=
=9Chey, this series is gonna be amazing, I=E2=80=99ve got a great team and =
relationships with big celebrities, we=E2=80=99re gonna do sequels for ages=
, get in on the ground floor of a new entertainment franchise that is basic=
ally the next Marvel or whatever, but with cats who enjoy marijuana.=E2=80=
=9D And then you sell shares in the production, entitling investors to a sh=
are of the money you make. You sell these shares=C2=A0on the internet, to a=
nyone who shows up, without bothering to check if they are =E2=80=9C  accre=
dited investors.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
That is, I think, fairly obviously a securities offering? And you will get =
in trouble if you sell the shares to the public and do not register the sal=
es with the US Securities and Exchange Commission.
But let=E2=80=99s change the hypothetical slightly. Let=E2=80=99s change ho=
w the shares work, in the following three ways:
=09You don=E2=80=99t call them =E2=80=9Cshares.=E2=80=9D Call them =E2=80=
=9Ctokens.=E2=80=9D=09You don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0actually=C2=A0promise holders =
any of the money you make. You say =E2=80=9Cif this series is a big hit and=
 spawns years of sequels, the value of these tokens will go up.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0Why=C2=A0will they go up? Oh, I don=E2=80=99t know, why does anything go=
 up? In 2021 you could just=C2=A0do=C2=A0this; you could say =E2=80=9Cthe t=
okens of this project will go up if the project is popular,=E2=80=9D even i=
f holders of the tokens are not entitled to any of the project=E2=80=99s re=
venue.=09Each token comes with a picture of one of the cats attached.

Is=C2=A0that=C2=A0a securities offering? Man, I don=E2=80=99t know. There a=
re arguments both ways:
=09Yes: Look, this is raising money to finance a project by selling bits of=
 the project to investors who hope to earn a speculative return. That is ju=
st classically   a security, =E2=80=9Can investment of money in a common en=
terprise with profits to come solely from the efforts of others.=E2=80=9D F=
rom the investors=E2=80=99 perspective, this trade is the same as selling s=
hares.=09No: There is no actual direct promise of profits! The tokens come =
with pictures of cats! They are just art, man! This is like Walt Disney rai=
sing money to make Mickey Mouse cartoons by selling drawings of the mouse! =
Sure those drawings will be worth more if Mickey Mouse is a huge hit and sp=
awns an animation and theme-park empire, but any artist=E2=80=99s work will=
 be more valuable if the artist becomes famous, and that doesn=E2=80=99t ma=
ke the art a security.

We have   talked about this issue before. The SEC very much takes the view =
that this sort of thing is a securities offering, and last month it  brough=
t an enforcement action against a company called Impact Theory LLC=C2=A0tha=
t raised $30 million by selling non-fungible tokens to fund, I don=E2=80=99=
t know, some sort of incomprehensible crypto project. Today  it came for St=
oner Cats:

The Securities and Exchange Commission today charged Stoner Cats 2 LLC (SC2=
) with conducting an unregistered offering of crypto asset securities in th=
e form of purported non-fungible tokens (NFTs) that raised approximately $8=
 million from investors to finance an animated web series called Stoner Cat=
s.
According to the SEC order, on July 27, 2021, SC2 offered and sold to inves=
tors more than 10,000 NFTs for approximately $800 each, selling out in 35 m=
inutes. The order finds that both before and after Stoner Cats NFTs were so=
ld to the public, SC2=E2=80=99s marketing campaign highlighted specific ben=
efits of owning them, including the option for owners to resell their NFTs =
on the secondary market. In addition, the order finds that, as part of the =
marketing campaign, the SC2 team emphasized its expertise as Hollywood prod=
ucers, its knowledge of crypto projects, and the well-known actors involved=
 in the web series, leading investors to expect profits because a successfu=
l web series could cause the resale value of the Stoner Cats NFTs in the se=
condary market to rise. Further, the order finds that SC2 configured the St=
oner Cats NFTs to provide SC2 a 2.5 percent royalty for each secondary mark=
et transaction in the NFTs and it encouraged individuals to buy and sell th=
e NFTs, leading purchasers to spend more than $20 million in at least 10,00=
0 transactions. According to the SEC=E2=80=99s order, SC2 violated the Secu=
rities Act of 1933 by offering and selling these crypto asset securities to=
 the public in an unregistered offering that was not exempt from registrati=
on.
=E2=80=9CRegardless of whether your offering involves beavers, chinchillas =
or animal-based NFTs, under the federal securities laws, it=E2=80=99s the e=
conomic reality of the offering =E2=80=93 not the labels you put on it or t=
he underlying objects =E2=80=93 that guides the determination of what=E2=80=
=99s an investment contract and therefore a security,=E2=80=9D said Gurbir =
S. Grewal, Director of the SEC=E2=80=99s Division of Enforcement. =E2=80=A6
Without admitting or denying the SEC=E2=80=99s findings, SC2 agreed to a ce=
ase-and-desist order and to pay a civil penalty of $1 million.

It also promised to =E2=80=9Cdestroy all NFTs in its possession or control.=
=E2=80=9D I don=E2=80=99t want to think about that.   There was a time when=
 you could probably record a video of yourself deleting an NFT and sell tha=
t video as an NFT, but that was=C2=A0very=C2=A02021.
I am not=C2=A0that=C2=A0sure that these pictures of cats were securities? I=
 see where the SEC is coming from: The Stoner Cats people were clearly rais=
ing money from investors to fund a project, and they were not selling the c=
ats to discerning art collectors. From  the SEC order:
Each Stoner Cats NFT was associated with a unique still image of one of the=
 characters in the Stoner Cats web series, with different expressions, appa=
rel, accessories, and backgrounds, resulting in a multitude of NFTs. Purcha=
sers could not choose their NFT in the offering, but instead received a ran=
dom allocation.
And:
While purchasers may =E2=80=9Cown=E2=80=9D their particular Stoner Cats NFT=
, SC2 specifically reserved all commercial rights to the underlying intelle=
ctual property, including the images of the characters.
And clearly at least some people were buying the cats for speculative purpo=
ses: =E2=80=9CAt least 20% of the Stoner Cats NFTs purchased in the offerin=
g were resold in the secondary market before the first episode of the Stone=
r Cats series aired,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cinvestors were also told that =
=E2=80=98the more successful the show, the more successful your NFT=E2=80=
=99 will be.=E2=80=9D
On the other hand, one benefit of buying the cats is that you could watch t=
he show: =E2=80=9CInvestors were told that the Stoner Cats NFT was analogou=
s to a =E2=80=98ticket=E2=80=99=C2=A0and that =E2=80=98if people don=E2=80=
=99t appreciate it, you can take that ticket and sell it.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D=
 A concert ticket is not a security! Even if the concert is sold out and yo=
u can resell your ticket for a profit! And there don=E2=80=99t seem to have=
 been any promises to share the profits of the project: People seemed to th=
ink that the tokens would go up in value due to some combination of (1) gen=
eral crypto enthusiasm and (2) maybe people would want to watch the show an=
d would buy the tokens to do so. They were=C2=A0speculative investments, su=
re, but that doesn=E2=80=99t make them securities.
Also I feel like the requirement that you have to own an NFT to watch the s=
how makes the NFT in some sense the opposite of a share of stock? There is =
a natural limitation on the economic value of the franchise if only a few t=
housand token holders can watch it: Each token can be more valuable, but th=
at value comes from exclusivity, not from the show being a big general hit.=
 There was no source of revenue=C2=A0other than the tokens.
But Stoner Cats settled, so a court won=E2=80=99t weigh in on this. Impact =
Theory settled too. There are a lot of little NFT projects that the SEC doe=
sn=E2=80=99t like, and it might be cheaper for them to settle and pay up th=
an it is to fight the SEC for years in court. It=E2=80=99s not clear that t=
hese sorts of NFTs are securities, as a legal matter, but as a practical ma=
tter they kind of are.

