      Mortgage assumption startup
   =20
 =20

Just conceptually it is an obvious trade:
=09I own a house with a $400,000 mortgage with a 3% interest rate, and I wa=
nt to sell it.=09You would like to buy my house for $500,000, putting 20% d=
own and borrowing $400,000.=09But interest rates have gone up a lot, and if=
 you got a $400,000 mortgage now, the interest rate would be 7%.=C2=A0=09Yo=
u can=E2=80=99t afford that, so you don=E2=80=99t borrow $400,000, so you d=
on=E2=80=99t buy my house.=09What if you could give me $100,000, move into =
the house, and take over my mortgage, making the 3% payments until it is pa=
id off? Then we are both better off.

Broadly speaking you could imagine two ways to do this:
=09We could call up my mortgage lender and say =E2=80=9Chey, everything abo=
ut this mortgage is gonna stay the same =E2=80=94=C2=A0same amount ($400,00=
0),
  [2]
=C2=A0same term (30 years or whatever),=C2=A0same rate (3%), same collatera=
l (my house), except there=E2=80=99ll be a different borrower (you, not me)=
. Are you cool with that?=E2=80=9D And then the lender says =E2=80=9Cyes,=
=E2=80=9D either out of the goodness of its heart or because we pay it a li=
ttle fee=C2=A0or because the original terms of the mortgage specifically=C2=
=A0allowed=C2=A0me to let someone else take over the mortgage.=09Magic? Lik=
e, we do some sleight of hand where we=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0call up my l=
ender to get its approval, but we structure a transaction between ourselves=
 that achieves this result. You give me $100,000, you move into the house, =
you send the mortgage checks to me, I forward them to my bank, we enter int=
o some sort of blood oath that makes me not have to worry about your credit=
 risk, I don=E2=80=99t know.

The first option is called =E2=80=9Cassuming=E2=80=9D the mortgage. General=
ly speaking if you call up a bank asking them to let you assume a 3% mortga=
ge, they will say no, because that is a money-losing trade for them.=C2=A0T=
he lender would much rather have me sell the house for $500,000 to a new bu=
yer who does not assume the mortgage, get its $400,000 below-market mortgag=
e paid back, and then issue a new $400,000 mortgage to the buyer at market =
rates (7%).
  [3]

But, in the US, some mortgages are, by their terms, assumable: The bank doe=
sn=E2=80=99t have to like it, but it can=E2=80=99t say no. In particular,  =
the Wall Street Journal reports:

Some 22% of active mortgages are part of the government programs that have =
assumption features, according to the mortgage-data and technology company =
Black Knight. That includes loans extended through the Department of Vetera=
ns Affairs and the Federal Housing Administration programs.
Few consumers know about the option, and fewer still follow through with it=
. The FHA has processed 3,349 assumptions in the fiscal year that ends Sept=
. 30, up from 2,566 in the year prior.

That Journal article is about a new company called Roam that is launching t=
o address that problem, mostly by telling people with assumable mortgages t=
hat they have assumable mortgages:

Raunaq Singh, Roam=E2=80=99s founder and chief executive officer, says his =
new company will find and advertise home listings attached to attractive as=
sumable mortgages. It is initially launching in Georgia, Arizona, Colorado,=
 Texas and Florida.
The company aims to help with the paperwork and other bureaucratic hoops. T=
hat means working with the seller=E2=80=99s mortgage company on behalf of t=
he buyer and seller.
=E2=80=9CHave you ever called someone every day until you get what you want=
ed?=E2=80=9D says Singh, who earlier in his career worked at the online rea=
l-estate company Opendoor. =E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s the kind of service we d=
o on your behalf.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

The =E2=80=9Cpaperwork and other bureaucratic hoops=E2=80=9D are driven not=
 only by old-fashioned banking processes but also by the fact we discussed =
above, that a bank doesn=E2=80=99t really=C2=A0want=C2=A0to keep a 3% mortg=
age outstanding if it doesn=E2=80=99t have to:

The startup could run up against the Luddite world of mortgage banking, whe=
re assumption documents are still often transmitted by fax machine. Lenders=
 sometimes drag their feet in processing assumptions because they earn only=
 a few hundred dollars for processing them, far less than for originating a=
 new mortgage, according to Ted Tozer, nonresident fellow at the Urban Inst=
itute=E2=80=99s Housing Finance Policy Center.
For loan assumptions to become popular, lenders will need to be allowed to =
earn more on them, Tozer says. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s not much you can do=
 with that if the lenders aren=E2=80=99t going to be efficiently processing=
 assumptions,=E2=80=9D he says.

This is fine, this is a useful service. I will say though that I would much=
=C2=A0rather=C2=A0be writing about a new fintech startup doing Option 2: fi=
nding some way for you to assume my mortgage=C2=A0without=C2=A0the bank pro=
cessing the assumption. Do the sleight of hand! Create value from nowhere! =
Oh I am not at all sure it could work or anything; I assume there=E2=80=99s=
 a reason no one has done it.
  [4]
=C2=A0But rates really were 3% pretty recently, and they really are 7% now,=
 and there really are a lot of 3% mortgages out there that are not=C2=A0ass=
umable by their terms, and if someone could find something to do with them =
that would be a good business.

