rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> brought an enforcement =
action</a> against a company called Impact Theory LLC=C2=A0that raised $30 =
million by selling non-fungible tokens to fund, I don=E2=80=99t know, some =
sort of incomprehensible crypto project. Today <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32699780.289424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZX=
dzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMy0xNzg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB42d12be0" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
"> it came for Stoner Cats</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Securities and Exchange Commission today c=
harged Stoner Cats 2 LLC (SC2) with conducting an unregistered offering of =
crypto asset securities in the form of purported non-fungible tokens (NFTs)=
 that raised approximately $8 million from investors to finance an animated=
 web series called Stoner Cats.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">According to the SEC order, on July 27, 2021, =
SC2 offered and sold to investors more than 10,000 NFTs for approximately $=
800 each, selling out in 35 minutes. The order finds that both before and a=
fter Stoner Cats NFTs were sold to the public, SC2=E2=80=99s marketing camp=
aign highlighted specific benefits of owning them, including the option for=
 owners to resell their NFTs on the secondary market. In addition, the orde=
r finds that, as part of the marketing campaign, the SC2 team emphasized it=
s expertise as Hollywood producers, its knowledge of crypto projects, and t=
he well-known actors involved in the web series, leading investors to expec=
t profits because a successful web series could cause the resale value of t=
he Stoner Cats NFTs in the secondary market to rise. Further, the order fin=
ds that SC2 configured the Stoner Cats NFTs to provide SC2 a 2.5 percent ro=
yalty for each secondary market transaction in the NFTs and it encouraged i=
ndividuals to buy and sell the NFTs, leading purchasers to spend more than =
$20 million in at least 10,000 transactions. According to the SEC=E2=80=99s=
 order, SC2 violated the Securities Act of 1933 by offering and selling the=
se crypto asset securities to the public in an unregistered offering that w=
as not exempt from registration.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CRegardless of whether your offering i=
nvolves beavers, chinchillas or animal-based NFTs, under the federal securi=
ties laws, it=E2=80=99s the economic reality of the offering =E2=80=93 not =
the labels you put on it or the underlying objects =E2=80=93 that guides th=
e determination of what=E2=80=99s an investment contract and therefore a se=
curity,=E2=80=9D said Gurbir S. Grewal, Director of the SEC=E2=80=99s Divis=
ion of Enforcement. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Without admitting or denying the SEC=E2=80=99s=
 findings, SC2 agreed to a cease-and-desist order and to pay a civil penalt=
y of $1 million.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It also promised to =E2=80=9Cdestroy all NFTs =
in its possession or control.=E2=80=9D I don=E2=80=99t want to think about =
that. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32699780.289=
424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDktMTA=
vZnVuZ2libGUtc2xpY2VzLW9mLW5vbi1mdW5naWJsZS10b2tlbnM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDkxMzIzX0=
1PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlc=
m09MjMwOTEzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBccf982=
f6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">  There was a time</a> when you could probably record a video =
of yourself deleting an NFT and sell that video as an NFT, but that was=C2=
=A0<em>very=C2=A0</em>2021.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am not=C2=A0<em>that=C2=A0</em>sure that the=
se pictures of cats were securities? I see where the SEC is coming from: Th=
e Stoner Cats people were clearly raising money from investors to fund a pr=
oject, and they were not selling the cats to discerning art collectors. Fro=
m <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32699780.289424/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9maWxlcy9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2FkbWluLzIwMjMvMzMtMTEyMzM=
ucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8915f368" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the SEC order</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Each Stoner Cats NFT was associate=
d with a unique still image of one of the characters in the Stoner Cats web=
 series, with different expressions, apparel, accessories, and backgrounds,=
 resulting in a multitude of NFTs. Purchasers could not choose their NFT in=
 the offering, but instead received a random allocation.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While purchasers may =E2=80=9Cown=
=E2=80=9D their particular Stoner Cats NFT, SC2 specifically reserved all c=
ommercial rights to the underlying intellectual property, including the ima=
ges of the characters.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And clearly at least some people were buying t=
he cats for speculative purposes: =E2=80=9CAt least 20% of the Stoner Cats =
NFTs purchased in the offering were resold in the secondary market before t=
he first episode of the Stoner Cats series aired,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cinv=
estors were also told that =E2=80=98the more successful the show, the more =
successful your NFT=E2=80=99 will be.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand, one benefit of buying the c=
ats is that you could watch the show: =E2=80=9CInvestors were told that the=
 Stoner Cats NFT was analogous to a =E2=80=98ticket=E2=80=99=C2=A0and that =
=E2=80=98if people don=E2=80=99t appreciate it, you can take that ticket an=
d sell it.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D A concert ticket is not a security! Even if th=
e concert is sold out and you can resell your ticket for a profit! And ther=
e don=E2=80=99t seem to have been any promises to share the profits of the =
project: People seemed to think that the tokens would go up in value due to=
 some combination of (1) general crypto enthusiasm and (2) maybe people wou=
ld want to watch the show and would buy the tokens to do so. They were=C2=
=A0<em>speculative investments</em>, sure, but that doesn=E2=80=99t make th=
em securities.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also I feel like the requirement that you have=
 to own an NFT to watch the show makes the NFT in some sense the opposite o=
f a share of stock? There is a natural limitation on the economic value of =
the franchise if only a few thousand token holders can watch it: Each token=
 can be more valuable, but that value comes from exclusivity, not from the =
show being a big general hit. There was no source of <em>revenue</em>=C2=A0=
other than the tokens.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But Stoner Cats settled, so a court won=E2=80=
=99t weigh in on this. Impact Theory settled too. There are a lot of little=
 NFT projects that the SEC doesn=E2=80=99t like, and it might be cheaper fo=
r them to settle and pay up than it is to fight the SEC for years in court.=
 It=E2=80=99s not clear that these sorts of NFTs are securities, as a legal=
 matter, but as a practical matter they kind of are.</p>
