<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Just conceptually it is an obvious trade:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">I own a house with a $400,000 mortgage=
 with a 3% interest rate, and I want to sell it.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin=
-bottom: 5px;">You would like to buy my house for $500,000, putting 20% dow=
n and borrowing $400,000.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">But inte=
rest rates have gone up a lot, and if you got a $400,000 mortgage now, the =
interest rate would be 7%.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Y=
ou can=E2=80=99t afford that, so you don=E2=80=99t borrow $400,000, so you =
don=E2=80=99t buy my house.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">What i=
f you could give me $100,000, move into the house, and take over my mortgag=
e, making the 3% payments until it is paid off? Then we are both better off=
.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Broadly speaking you could imagine two ways to=
 do this:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">We could call up my mortgage lender a=
nd say =E2=80=9Chey, everything about this mortgage is gonna stay the same =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0same amount ($400,000),<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#=
footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: no=
ne !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-bl=
ock;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0same term (30 years or whatever),=C2=A0same rate (3%), same colla=
teral (my house), except there=E2=80=99ll be a different borrower (you, not=
 me). Are you cool with that?=E2=80=9D And then the lender says =E2=80=9Cye=
s,=E2=80=9D either out of the goodness of its heart or because we pay it a =
little fee=C2=A0or because the original terms of the mortgage specifically=
=C2=A0<em>allowed=C2=A0</em>me to let someone else take over the mortgage.<=
/li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Magic? Like, we do some sleight of=
 hand where we=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>call up my lender to get it=
s approval, but we structure a transaction between ourselves that achieves =
this result. You give me $100,000, you move into the house, you send the mo=
rtgage checks to me, I forward them to my bank, we enter into some sort of =
blood oath that makes me not have to worry about your credit risk, I don=E2=
=80=99t know.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The first option is called =E2=80=9Cassuming=
=E2=80=9D the mortgage. Generally speaking if you call up a bank asking the=
m to let you assume a 3% mortgage, they will say no, because that is a mone=
y-losing trade for them.=C2=A0The lender would much rather have me sell the=
 house for $500,000 to a new buyer who does not assume the mortgage, get it=
s $400,000 below-market mortgage paid back, and then issue a new $400,000 m=
ortgage to the buyer at market rates (7%).<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But, in the US, some mortgages are, by their t=
erms, assumable: The bank doesn=E2=80=99t have to like it, but it can=E2=80=
=99t say no. In particular, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
com/click/32699780.289424/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9wZXJzb25hbC1maW5hbmNlL=
21vcnRnYWdlcy9hLTMtbW9ydGdhZ2UtcmF0ZS1pbi1hLTctd29ybGQtdGhpcy1zdGFydHVwLXNh=
eXMtaXQtY2FuLWRvLXRoYXQtNmFmYTg1YWE_bW9kPWhwX2xlYWRfcG9zMg/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB0adc8f12" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;"> the Wall Street Journal reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some 22% of active mortgages are part of the g=
overnment programs that have assumption features, according to the mortgage=
-data and technology company Black Knight. That includes loans extended thr=
ough the Department of Veterans Affairs and the Federal Housing Administrat=
ion programs.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Few consumers know about the option, and fewer=
 still follow through with it. The FHA has processed 3,349 assumptions in t=
he fiscal year that ends Sept. 30, up from 2,566 in the year prior.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That Journal article is about a new company ca=
lled Roam that is launching to address that problem, mostly by telling peop=
le with assumable mortgages that they have assumable mortgages:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Raunaq Singh, Roam=E2=80=99s founder and chief=
 executive officer, says his new company will find and advertise home listi=
ngs attached to attractive assumable mortgages. It is initially launching i=
n Georgia, Arizona, Colorado, Texas and Florida.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The company aims to help with the paperwork an=
d other bureaucratic hoops. That means working with the seller=E2=80=99s mo=
rtgage company on behalf of the buyer and seller.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CHave you ever called someone every da=
y until you get what you wanted?=E2=80=9D says Singh, who earlier in his ca=
reer worked at the online real-estate company Opendoor. =E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=
=99s the kind of service we do on your behalf.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The =E2=80=9Cpaperwork and other bureaucratic =
hoops=E2=80=9D are driven not only by old-fashioned banking processes but a=
lso by the fact we discussed above, that a bank doesn=E2=80=99t really=C2=
=A0<em>want=C2=A0</em>to keep a 3% mortgage outstanding if it doesn=E2=80=
=99t have to:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The startup could run up against the Luddite w=
orld of mortgage banking, where assumption documents are still often transm=
itted by fax machine. Lenders sometimes drag their feet in processing assum=
ptions because they earn only a few hundred dollars for processing them, fa=
r less than for originating a new mortgage, according to Ted Tozer, nonresi=
dent fellow at the Urban Institute=E2=80=99s Housing Finance Policy Center.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For loan assumptions to become popular, lender=
s will need to be allowed to earn more on them, Tozer says. =E2=80=9CThere=
=E2=80=99s not much you can do with that if the lenders aren=E2=80=99t goin=
g to be efficiently processing assumptions,=E2=80=9D he says.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is fine, this is a useful service. I will=
 say though that I would much=C2=A0<em>rather=C2=A0</em>be writing about a =
new fintech startup doing Option 2: finding some way for you to assume my m=
ortgage=C2=A0<em>without=C2=A0</em>the bank processing the assumption. Do t=
he sleight of hand! Create value from nowhere! Oh I am not at all sure it c=
ould <em>work </em>or anything; I assume there=E2=80=99s a reason no one ha=
s done it.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-co=
lor: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0But rates really were 3% pretty recently, and they really are 7% =
now, and there really are a lot of 3% mortgages out there that are <em>not=
=C2=A0</em>assumable by their terms, and if someone could find something to=
 do with them that would be a good business.</p>
